    id: "ch-10", number: 10, title: "The Night", minutes: 8, status: "Editing",
    paragraphs: [
      "In a grand opera house where not a single seat was occupied, where rows of red chairs sat empty in the dark and the stage held no audience's expectation — two figures stood beneath the lights.",
      "One was a woman lying on the stage floor, her light blue dress spread around her. Her face was unclear, as faces in dreams often are — but what could be seen was a thin line of crimson running from her forehead, moving slowly, like a petal stained by something it shouldn't have touched.",
      "The other was a man, standing, both arms extended toward the woman. His hands held something. A revolver. Smoke curled from the muzzle. The man lowered his arm. His face was visible. It was Cyrus.",
      "* * *",
      "He gasped awake. The familiar ceiling. Sweat cooling at his temples. His breath arriving in shallow pulls until he caught it. *A dream. Sure doesn't feel like one.*",
      "He sat up and wiped his face. Hallucinations of fire and a dying wife. The persistent sense of invisible eyes in the street. And now a dream in which he stood over a woman with a smoking gun in his hand. *I should have my mental health examined before any of this gets worse.*",
      "A small tug at his thigh pulled him back. He looked down. Cassandra lay beside him, turned slightly inward, her breathing just visible in the stillness. He reached out and ran his fingers gently through her hair, careful not to wake her. *Nevermind. I'm well enough.*",
      "He lay back down. As he settled against the pillow, something small occurred to him. *I've woken before her two days in a row now.* He turned the observation over once, couldn't make anything of it, and let sleep take him.",
      "* * *",
      "He was shaken awake some hours later by a firm, familiar hand. The room was bright. Cassandra stood over him. “Rise and shine, Mr. Deep-Sleeper. Breakfast is ready.” *I was awake before you. You just didn't see it.*",
      "After breakfast he changed into his work clothes and stood at the front door. The day had come. Whatever truth lived inside that yellow forest, he was going to find it. He reached for the knob. A tug at his sleeve stopped him.",
      "He turned. Cassandra was holding the fabric of his sleeve without looking up, her gaze directed at the floor. When she finally raised her face, something was tight in it — something she had been holding since the moment she woke up. “Be careful,” she said. The words were quiet. Not a command. A request. “I will,” he said.",
      "He opened the door and stepped out. Howard stood at the curb. A carriage waited beside him, a horse in harness, no driver's seat occupied. Cyrus walked up without returning the greeting. “Tell me the truth. What did you mean when you said you saw Bruce commit suicide?”",
      "Howard blinked — genuinely, briefly — then smoothed over it. “I said what?” “Yesterday. In your office. You said you saw it. Explain that.” Passersby glanced over. Howard stepped forward and covered Cyrus's mouth with his palm. “Shh.”",
      "“Honestly? Even if I told you, you wouldn't understand it.” “What does that mean?” “Perhaps you'll understand once you've been to the forest.” “That's not an answer. I want the truth from you.” Howard's expression shifted — not to anger, but to something flatter and harder. “I am paying you, Cyrus. Or have you forgotten that?”",
      "The authority in it closed around the conversation. “Or perhaps you no longer want the offer.” It wasn't a question. Cyrus clenched his jaw and climbed up onto the carriage seat. “Where is the bodyguard?” “Already with you.” He looked inside the carriage. Empty. “There's no one in here.” “Believe me just this once. And if you decide not to go — the offer ends the moment you step down.”",
      "Cyrus sat for a long moment. Then he picked up the reins. As the carriage moved and the distance between them grew, Howard's expression shifted into something quiet and private — a slight curve at the corner of his mouth that no one around him was close enough to see.",
    ],
    notes: [
      { paragraph: 0, label: "The empty opera house", body: "Cyrus's role in the whole novel, in one image: a stage, an audience of no one, and a witness who has already done the thing.", kind: "creative" },
      { paragraph: 16, label: "Howard's smile", body: "This is the reader's confirmation that Cyrus is being handled, not helped. From here on the boss is antagonist by weight, not by declaration.", kind: "technical" },
    ],
