    id: "ch-15", number: 15, title: "Fracture", minutes: 4, status: "Editing",
    paragraphs: [
      "The morning Cassandra made breakfast and he couldn't eat it was the morning he understood that something in him had physically changed.",
      "It wasn't grief refusing the food. Grief he could have named and managed. This was different—a wrongness rooted somewhere below the stomach, below reason, in the part of the body that operates on older instructions than the mind. The smell of warm food triggered something involuntary, a recoil that came before the thought arrived, and by the time he understood what was happening he had already pushed back from the table.",
      "\"You haven't eaten since before you left,\" Cassandra said, watching him carefully.",
      "\"I know.\"",
      "\"That was three days ago.\"",
      "\"I know, Cass.\"",
      "She didn't push further. She put a cloth over his portion and set it aside and finished her own meal in the quiet that had become their new default register.",
      "He went to the sink and ran the water cold and drank from his cupped hands, which he could manage. He straightened up and looked at his reflection in the window glass above the sink.",
      "For just a moment—half a second, maybe less—he saw someone standing behind him.",
      "Scrawny. Bearded. Pale as something that had been underground too long.",
      "He turned around immediately. The kitchen was empty. Cassandra was at the table with her back to him, unaware.",
      "Cyrus gripped the edge of the sink and breathed through his nose until his pulse settled. Then he let go, dried his hands on his trousers, and went to change for work.",
      "He told himself it was exhaustion. He told himself three days without food and two nights of broken sleep were enough to produce a trick of the eye. He told himself this because the alternative—that what happened in the cave had done something real and permanent to his perception—was a door he wasn't ready to open. Not yet.",
      "He was nearly dressed when the whisper came.",
      "He went still.",
      "It was faint enough that he might have dismissed it as the sound of the street outside, or a neighbor through the wall, except that it had no direction. It didn't come from the window or the door or any point in the room. It came from inside, from somewhere below thought, and it was not in any language he recognized.",
      "Then it was gone.",
      "Cyrus stood in the middle of the room for a long moment. Cassandra's footsteps moved through the house somewhere behind him.",
      "I should tell her.",
      "He finished dressing and said nothing.",
    ],
