    id: "ch-17", number: 17, title: "Judgement", minutes: 5, status: "Editing",
    paragraphs: [
      "Evening arrived by the time Cyrus reached home. The orange light that came with it flattened the shadows and made the street look like a painting of itself.",
      "Cassandra was at the table when he came in. She looked up immediately—watchful in the way she'd been watchful since he came back. A new habit. He noticed it and said nothing about it.",
      "\"Officers came today,\" she said.",
      "He hung his coat by the door. \"I expected that.\"",
      "\"They're coming back tonight.\"",
      "He nodded and sat. She watched him from across the table with her hands folded, and he could see the question she was holding—not whether to ask it, but how.",
      "\"Cyrus.\" Her voice was steady. \"Did you kill Bruce Hill?\"",
      "He looked at her directly. She deserved that much.",
      "\"Yes.\"",
      "Cassandra held his gaze for a long moment. Then she looked down at the table—not in withdrawal, just thinking. He waited.",
      "\"I knew that forest was dangerous,\" she said finally. \"We both did. I let you go anyway because of the money.\" She pressed her lips together. \"If I'd refused—if I'd actually put my foot down instead of just worrying quietly—you wouldn't have been in that cave.\"",
      "\"That's not your fault, Cass.\"",
      "\"I'm not saying it's my fault. I'm saying I had a choice and I made one and I have to live with that too.\" She looked up. \"You don't get to carry all of this alone just because your hands were the ones holding the gun.\"",
      "He didn't have an answer for that. It wasn't the kind of thing that had an answer—it was the kind of thing that had to be sat with.",
      "Knock. Knock.",
      "Both of them went still.",
      "Cassandra rose and answered the door.",
      "Two figures stood on the step. May—her eyes red-rimmed, her composure assembled from visible effort—and beside her, wearing the pressed uniform of an officer, a man Cyrus recognized the moment he looked past the uniform.",
      "Stephen Mestizo.",
      "Of course.",
      "His pale eyes found Cyrus across the room with the calm of someone who is very good at not reacting to things. He looked, in his officer's clothes, exactly as he'd looked in his bodyguard's tuxedo—unhurried, detached, someone who had arranged himself to be here and was exactly where he intended to be.",
      "May pointed at Cyrus. Her hand was steady, which seemed to cost her something.",
      "\"That's him. He's the one who came back with my husband's body.\"",
      "Stephen stepped inside with a small nod toward Cassandra, who moved aside. He stopped a few feet from Cyrus and looked at him with the professional blankness of a man who had never met him before in his life.",
      "\"Mr. Cyrus. I'm required to ask you several questions regarding the death of Bruce Hill.\" A brief pause. \"Formally.\"",
      "The emphasis on that last word was so small that only someone who had spent time in a dark cave with the man would have caught it. Cyrus caught it.",
      "May stepped forward. Her composure cracked for a moment—just a moment—before she pulled it back.",
      "\"He promised me,\" she said quietly, which was somehow worse than when she had been loud on the road. \"He told me he'd try to bring Bruce back. He took my money and he went, and this is what he came home with.\"",
      "Cassandra reached for May's arm. May let her.",
      "Stephen's eyes returned to Cyrus. Professional. Waiting.",
      "\"Did you kill Bruce Hill?\"",
      "The question settled into the room.",
      "Cyrus could have explained. He knew exactly what he would say—the bodyguard standing in this very room who had handed him the gun, had ordered him to fire, who now wore a different uniform and a different expression and would deny every word of it. He could see exactly how that conversation would go.",
      "He could also see May's face.",
      "\"Yes,\" he said.",
      "May exhaled—a sharp, involuntary sound that was neither relief nor satisfaction. Cassandra's hand tightened on her arm.",
      "Stephen wrote something in the small notebook he'd produced from his breast pocket. His handwriting was neat. Of course it was.",
      "\"You'll come in tomorrow morning for formal questioning. Eight o'clock.\"",
      "\"I'll be there,\" Cyrus said.",
      "Stephen glanced up from the notebook and held Cyrus's gaze for one additional second. In it was something that wasn't quite acknowledgment and wasn't quite warning and was very deliberately something other than what it actually was.",
      "Then he closed the notebook, offered a small professional nod to the room in general, and turned toward the door.",
      "May followed. At the threshold she paused and looked back at Cyrus—not with hatred now, or not only with hatred—with the particular exhausted grief of someone who had wanted an explanation and had accepted that none was coming.",
      "The door closed.",
      "Cassandra came to stand beside him. Neither of them spoke. Outside, footsteps retreated down the path, and then the street sounds returned to their ordinary rhythm as though nothing unusual had happened on this particular evening.",
      "\"Why didn't you defend yourself?\" she asked finally. \"You could have said something.\"",
      "Cyrus looked at the closed door for a moment.",
      "\"Because the man who could corroborate my story was standing in this room wearing a different hat,\" he said. \"And because May Hill lost her husband. She deserves to see someone answer for that, even if the answer is incomplete.\"",
      "Cassandra was quiet. Then:",
      "\"And what do you deserve?\"",
      "He didn't answer that. He wasn't sure he had one yet.",
      "He went to the kitchen and forced himself to eat something small—bread, water, nothing complicated—standing at the counter because sitting felt like too much ceremony for an act of pure obligation. The food stayed down. He counted that as a small victory and didn't push further.",
      "That night he lay in the dark beside Cassandra and listened to the house settle. He tried to take stock of what he was.",
      "A journalist. A husband. A father-to-be. A man who had fired a gun in a cave and couldn't fully explain why.",
      "And now, apparently, something else—something without a name he trusted yet, something that let him hear conversations from three streets away and showed him dead men in mirrors.",
      "The whisper came again just before sleep—faint, directionless, in that language that wasn't a language. He didn't cover his ears. He lay still and listened to it the way you listen to rain falling somewhere else, and after a while it faded, and he slept.",
      "In the morning he would go and answer questions from a man who already knew all the answers. He would sit in a room and tell a story that was true and incomplete and watch Stephen Mestizo write it down in neat handwriting.",
      "But that was morning.",
      "For now he was just a man in a small house with a wife beside him and something new and nameless living in the space where certainty used to be.",
      "He closed his eyes.",
      "The whisper faded.",
      "He slept.",
    ],
